This topic describes how to install command-line tools required to install Spring Cloud Data Flow for Kubernetes.

## <a id='overview'></a> Overview

Command-line tools required to install Spring Cloud Data Flow for Kubernetes include the k14s utilities `kapp` and `kbld` as well as the utility `yq`.

* The `kapp` utility is a deployment tool with the concept of a "Kubernetes application": a set of resources with the same label.
  For more information about `kapp`, consult [get-kapp.io](https://get-kapp.io/).

* The `kbld` utility manipulates and replaces container images used in Kubernetes configuration files.
  For more information about `kbld`, consult [get-kbld.io](https://get-kbld.io/).

* The `yq` utility is a command-line YAML processor.  The aim of the project is to be the `jq` or `sed` of YAML files.  For more information consult (https://github.com/makefarah/yq).

For more information about the k14s utilities, consult [k14s.io](https://k14s.io).

To install the `kapp` and `kbld` tools, follow the procedures below for your operating system to obtain them from [VMware Tanzu Network](https://network.pivotal.io/products/p-scdf-for-kubernetes). Binaries are provided only for 64-bit architectures.


## <a id='macos'></a> macOS

This section describes how to install `kapp`, `kbld`, and `yq` on macOS.


### <a id='macos-kapp'></a> kapp

This section describes how to install the `kapp` utility on macOS.


1. Navigate to <a href="https://network.pivotal.io/">VMware Tanzu Network</a> and log in.

1. Click **kapp**.

1. Click **kapp - macOS** to download the <code>kapp</code> binary.

1. Rename the downloaded binary to <code>kapp</code>.

1. On the command line, run the following command to make the <code>kapp</code> binary executable:
  <pre>$ chmod +x kapp</pre>

1. Move the binary into your <code>PATH</code>. For example:
  <pre>$ mv kapp /usr/local/bin/kapp</pre>


